      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your code leaks memory because you allocate a new `Order` with `new` everywhere but never deallocate it with `delete` when `processOrder` returns. To fix this, you should return ownership instead of passing a pointer, for example by changing the function to `void processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> order)` and passing `std::make_unique<Order>(data)`. This ensures the smart pointer automatically deletes the object when it goes out of scope, preventing memory leaks and typo-based errors.",
