      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so what if we need multiple parts of the system to reference the same order object simultaneously? would shared_ptr be better there? also is the atomic reference counting in shared_ptr going to add too much latency for an HFT setup? i'm worried about any extra overhead.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, `std::shared_ptr` is the correct choice when multiple parts need to reference the same object simultaneously, as its reference-counting mechanism automatically manages ownership. Regarding latency in high-frequency trading, `std::shared_ptr` is generally very lightweight; the atomic increment/decrement operations it uses are extremely fast and typically negligible compared to network RTT or market data parsing delays.\n\nHowever, you must be extremely careful with cursorless allocation patterns like `new` calls on a hot path, as the overhead of creating or managing temporary shared pointers *outside* of critical inner loops is usually unavoidable. For HFT, the optimal solution is often to keep order objects in a thread-local or ring-buffer structure accessed exclusively by unique pointers or references, reserving dynamic `shared_ptr` allocation only for long-lived finalization states, not for instant order execution.",
      "source": "target",
